As p = P (β > 1/X) and is the probability of an outbreak from one species and so small, the way in which the probability of an outbreak increases with the number of susceptibles depends on the assumptions made about the upper tail of the probability density function of β


As β is a proportion, it can take values between 0 and 1 only, but in practice it takes values close to 0 and it seems reasonable to assume that, in the upper tail at least, larger values become less likely. A simple assumption is therefore that, in the upper tail, the probability density function decays exponentially as β increases. That is, it is proportional to a fraction raised to the power of β. It can be shown that this corresponds to the upper tail of an exponential distribution with parameter, θ where θ is the mean, so that the cumulative distribution function is F(β) = 1 – exp (-β/θ).

